<h1>Connekt — Detailed User & Technical Guide</h1>
<p>This document explains how to navigate and operate the Connekt application, and describes how the key features work under the hood. It is formatted as HTML so Microsoft Word can open it; use <strong>File → Save As → Word Document (.docx)</strong> to create a native Word file.</p>

<h2>Table of Contents</h2>
<ol>
  <li>Quick Start</li>
  <li>Top-level Navigation &amp; UI</li>
  <li>Primary User Flows</li>
  <li>Admin &amp; Moderation</li>
  <li>Data Model &amp; APIs</li>
  <li>Localization &amp; Theme</li>
  <li>Environment &amp; Deployment</li>
  <li>System Requirements</li>
  <li>Software Requirements</li>
  <li>User Roles &amp; Permissions</li>
  <li>Login &amp; Logout</li>
  <li>Dashboards Overview</li>
  <li>Security Guidelines</li>
  <li>Troubleshooting</li>
  <li>FAQ</li>
  <li>Glossary</li>
  <li>Appendix — File map</li>
</ol>

<h2>1. Quick Start</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Install dependencies: <code>npm install</code>.</li>
  <li>Create a <code>.env.local</code> with Supabase keys and <code>NEXTAUTH_URL</code>.</li>
  <li>Apply the database schema in <code>supabase_schema.sql</code> to your Supabase project.</li>
  <li>Start locally: <code>npm run dev</code> and open <a href="http://localhost:3000">http://localhost:3000</a>.</li>
</ul>

<h2>2. Top-level Navigation &amp; UI</h2>
<p>The main app navigation is implemented in <code>src/components/Navigation.tsx</code>. Key UI components include:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Header / Navigation:</strong> Primary links to Home, Jobs, Listings, Post, Dashboard, Profile, and Admin (for authorized users).</li>
  <li><strong>Locale Switcher:</strong> <code>src/components/LocaleSwitcher.tsx</code> toggles English/French and updates localized URLs under <code>/en</code> and <code>/fr</code>.</li>
  <li><strong>Theme Toggle:</strong> <code>src/components/ThemeToggle.tsx</code> toggles dark/light mode and stores preference in <code>localStorage</code>.</li>
  <li><strong>Splash/Loader:</strong> <code>src/components/SplashLoader.tsx</code> displays while initial app data loads.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Navigation behavior</h3>
<p>Routes are localized under <code>src/app/[locale]</code>. The app loads route-specific translation JSON from <code>src/messages</code> and renders server-side where possible using Next.js App Router conventions.</p>

<h2>3. Primary User Flows</h2>

<h3>Applicant (Student)</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Sign up or sign in on the Auth page. Authentication is handled by Supabase through <code>src/lib/supabase.ts</code>.</li>
  <li>Complete your profile at <code>/[locale]/profile</code>, including headline, skills, experience, education, and resume link.</li>
  <li>Browse jobs at <code>/[locale]/jobs</code> and use filters, search, and sort tools.</li>
  <li>View job details at <code>/[locale]/jobs/[jobId]</code> and click <em>Apply</em> to submit an application.</li>
  <li>Track submissions at <code>/[locale]/applications</code>, with statuses such as pending, accepted, or rejected.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Recruiter / Employer</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Sign in with recruiter credentials. Request elevated access from an admin if needed.</li>
  <li>Post a job via <code>/[locale]/post</code>. Provide title, description, location, tags, deadline, and optional screening questions.</li>
  <li>Manage postings under <code>/[locale]/listings</code> or <code>/[locale]/jobs</code>. Edit, pause, or remove listings.</li>
  <li>Review applicants at <code>/[locale]/applicants/[jobId]</code>, add private notes, and update application status.</li>
</ol>

<h2>4. Admin &amp; Moderation</h2>
<p>Admin pages are under <code>src/app/[locale]/admin</code>. Admin responsibilities include:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Approving or rejecting job postings in Job Moderation.</li>
  <li>Reviewing and bulk-managing applications in Applications Oversight.</li>
  <li>Managing user roles, deactivating/reactivating accounts, and investigating suspicious activity.</li>
</ul>

<h3>How admin auth works</h3>
<p>Server-side admin checks are implemented in <code>src/lib/adminAuth.ts</code>. API routes in <code>src/app/api/admin</code> validate requests with the Supabase service role key and role flags stored in the database. Never expose <code>SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY</code> to the client.</p>

<h2>5. Data Model &amp; APIs</h2>
<p>The key domain model is built around users, jobs, and applications. The database schema is defined in <code>supabase_schema.sql</code>.</p>
<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Table</th>
      <th>Purpose</th>
      <th>Key Fields</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><code>profiles</code></td>
      <td>User profile metadata mapped to Auth users.</td>
      <td><code>user_id</code>, <code>name</code>, <code>headline</code>, <code>skills</code>, <code>role</code>, <code>resume_url</code></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><code>jobs</code></td>
      <td>Job postings created by recruiters.</td>
      <td><code>title</code>, <code>description</code>, <code>owner_id</code>, <code>status</code>, <code>location</code>, <code>tags</code>, <code>deadline</code></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><code>applications</code></td>
      <td>Applications submitted by students for jobs.</td>
      <td><code>job_id</code>, <code>profile_id</code>, <code>status</code>, <code>resume_url</code>, <code>notes</code>, <code>submitted_at</code></td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h3>API route patterns</h3>
<p>Server handlers live under <code>src/app/api</code>. Public APIs serve the client, and admin APIs are under <code>src/app/api/admin</code>. Always fetch admin-level data server-side.</p>

<h4>Example: fetching applications server-side</h4>
<pre><code>import { createAdminClient } from '@/lib/supabase-admin'

export async function GET(request) {
  const supabase = createAdminClient()
  const { data, error } = await supabase.from('applications').select('*')
  if (error) return new Response(JSON.stringify({ error: error.message }), { status: 500 })
  return new Response(JSON.stringify(data), { status: 200 })
}
</code></pre>

<h2>6. Localization &amp; Theme</h2>
<p>Localization files are stored in <code>src/messages</code> and are grouped by route. To add a new locale:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Create a new locale folder under <code>src/app</code> (for example, <code>/es</code>).</li>
  <li>Add translated JSON files under the corresponding folder in <code>src/messages</code>.</li>
  <li>Update navigation definitions in <code>src/i18n/navigation.ts</code>.</li>
</ol>
<p>The theme toggle is implemented in <code>src/components/ThemeToggle.tsx</code>. It stores the selected mode in <code>localStorage</code> so the preference persists across reloads.</p>

<h2>7. Environment &amp; Deployment</h2>
<p>Required environment variables include:</p>
<ul>
  <li><code>NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL</code></li>
  <li><code>NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY</code></li>
  <li><code>SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY</code> (server-only)</li>
  <li><code>NEXTAUTH_URL</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Deploy on Vercel for automatic Next.js optimizations. Set the environment variables in your Vercel project dashboard and ensure the deployed domain matches <code>NEXTAUTH_URL</code>.</p>

